<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLAMES GET A VICTORY, KEY INJURY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBYN NORWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Another Mighty Duck game, another injured opponent. 
</P>
<P>
 Andrei Trefilov, Calgary's standout rookie goaltender, became the latest 
casualty when he left Wednesday night's game on a stretcher with an 
undetermined injury to his right knee late in the second period of the Ducks' 
4-2 loss in front of 17,174 at Anaheim Arena. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks are suddenly bad news for the other guys, and not just by hanging 
close in the standings. 
</P>
<P>
 Winnipeg's Teemu Selanne suffered a partially torn Achilles' tendon against 
the Ducks last week, and the Kings had a passel of injuries in their victory 
over the Ducks on Saturday -- Gary Shuchuk hurt his knee, Luc Robitaille had a 
minor ankle injury, and Wayne Gretzky was cut on the gum, the nose or nowhere 
at all, depending on whom you talk to. 
</P>
<P>
 At least this time, Duck defenseman Don McSween had nothing to do with it. 
McSween accidentally cut Selanne with his skate blade, was in on a collision 
with Shuchuk and was the unintentional perpetrator of the controversial 
high-sticking major against Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
 Trefilov was hurt when he tried to make a sudden move in the crease but didn't 
appear to be hit by a Duck. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was not a serious collision or anything, he just goes down in a funny 
manner," said Calgary Coach Dave King, who reported that Trefilov was taken to 
a hospital and there was concern about ligament damage. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks were trying to pick up a point or two against the top team in the 
Pacific Division, but they ended up learning what it feels like to play 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 The score was tied, 2-2, entering the third, but the Ducks made a couple of 
errors and Calgary's Robert Reichel scored twice to claim two points for the 
Flames. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had a chance to make up some ground tonight because of the Kings' loss 
(6-4 to Edmonton), but we had a couple of mental breakdowns that cost us 
goals," right wing Terry Yake said. "They just waited for us to make the 
mistakes, so in a sense they beat us at our own game." 
</P>
<P>
 Reichel scored the go-ahead goal at 2:05 after picking off a pass by Duck 
defenseman Bill Houlder in the Duck zone and beating goalie Ron Tugnutt from 
high in the slot. 
</P>
<P>
 Tugnutt, making his first start since Jan. 16, didn't appear to make much of a 
move to stop the shot, but the puck took a bit of a bad bounce after being 
partially deflected by a defenseman's stick. 
</P>
<P>
 Reichel gave the Flames a cushion at 14:55 with his 22nd goal of the season 
when Calgary got out on a 3-on-1 rush with McSween the only player back. 
</P>
<P>
 "Obviously it was a disappointing loss," Duck Coach Ron Wilson said. "It was a 
strange goal on the third one. Then they just went into a defensive shell. Once 
they got that one-goal lead, they pretty much shut us down." 
</P>
<P>
 Trefilov, 24, had consecutive shutouts this season and entered the game with a 
2.47 goals-against average. With Mike Vernon on the verge of recovering from a 
twisted knee, he has been crucial to the Flames. 
</P>
<P>
 Trefilov went down in the crease as Tim Sweeney swung his stick in an attempt 
to swat in a rebound, but television replays showed no contact. 
</P>
<P>
 With medical personnel working deliberately to move Trefilov to a stretcher 
and carry him off the ice and only 5.5 seconds remaining in the period, referee 
Ron Hoggarth sent the teams into the dressing rooms early. 
</P>
<P>
 Trevor Kidd took over in goal, but not much was asked immediately from him. 
The Ducks had a harmless shot in the final seconds of the second period, but 
didn't manage another until 11:28 of the third. 
</P>
<P>
 Joe Nieuwendyk gave Calgary a 1-0 lead at 10:55 of the first, but the Ducks 
evened the score at 2:15 of the second on Joe Sacco's 65-foot slap shot from 
the edge of the center faceoff circle. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks led, 2-1, after Yake scored his 16th goal of the season at 14:48 of 
the second, but Calgary came right back, with Gary Roberts tying the score 59 
seconds later. 
</P>
<P>
 And once they got the lead, the Flames focused on defense. 
</P>
<P>
 "Calgary did the exact same to us as we're supposed to do to them," Yake said. 
</P>
<P>
 Duck Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Anatoli Semenov, who played two games after returning from a seven-week layoff 
with a dislocated left elbow, missed a second consecutive game because of 
soreness in the elbow. Defenseman Alexei Kasatonov (bruised right foot) was 
also scratched for a second consecutive game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
