<HEADLINE>
<P>
13 OCC PLAYERS HEADED TO FOUR-YEAR COLLEGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE KRESAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange Coast, the dominant Orange County football team this season, also has 
sent the most players to four-year colleges. The Pirates (8-3) have 13 players 
advancing, including three to Pac-10 schools. 
</P>
<P>
 OCC's Justin Sogoian, who led the Mission Conference in punting, signed with 
UCLA. Israel Ifeanya, a defensive end from Nigeria, is going to USC. Anthoni 
Davis, a defensive back, is headed for Arizona State. 
</P>
<P>
 Noa Pua, who with Ifeanya gave OCC the quickest defensive ends in the 
conference, signed with San Diego State. 
</P>
<P>
 Todd Mather, who started most of two seasons at quarterback for OCC, is 
attending Tennessee Martin. 
</P>
<P>
 Saddleback's Scott von der Ahe, the only first-team J.C. Grid-Wire 
All-American from Orange County this season, signed with Iowa. Von der Ahe set 
the Saddleback career mark for tackles with 206 and sacks with 22 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
 Rancho Santiago's Jesse Gomez and George Burge, both powerful offensive 
linemen, signed with USC and New Mexico State. It will be the second trip to a 
Pac-10 school for Gomez, who signed with Oregon in 1990 after playing at Santa 
Ana High. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott Caringella, a defensive back from Golden West, signed with Northern 
Illinois, and teammate Tafa Jefferson, another in a long line of standout 
offensive linemen for the Rustlers, signed with Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
 Josh Nelson (quarterback) and Ryan Roskelly (wide receiver/kick returner) of 
Fullerton also signed. Nelson is going to Mississippi and Roskelly to Memphis 
State. Local Community College Signings 
</P>
