<P>
CITY HALL JOURNAL: PICO RIVERA; LARGE HOUSING PROJECT RECEIVES CITY APPROVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANN GRIFFITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved a controversial housing project on 12.6 acres at 
the intersection of Washington and Rosemead boulevards, ending three years of 
wrangling. 
</P>
<P>
 Critics said the project, which will include 116 single-family houses and 150 
apartments, is too big for the site and will create traffic problems. The 
development is across the street from Northrop Corp. Other residents questioned 
the decision to include a mixture of low- and moderate-income residences with 
more expensive homes. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials, however, said the project means an improvement, replacing 
aging buildings with new homes. Construction is expected to begin by early next 
year and the residences should be finished within three years. ANN GRIFFITH 
