<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SMALL BUSINESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Susan Christian / Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Entrepreneurs: Numerous executives who lost their jobs to layoffs consider 
starting a business of their own. The Executive Entrepreneur Program, to be 
launched at the end of this month, could help point them in the right 
direction. 
</P>
<P>
 The federally funded program will be conducted by Infotec Training Institute, 
a division of Infotec Development Inc., which trains corporate employees in 
application and systems software. Santa Ana-based Infotec Development, Orange 
County's largest Latino-owned company, makes computer software. 
</P>
<P>
 The program is free to participants. The first class will run for three 
months, three times a week. After its debut in Orange County, the program is 
expected to expand to Los Angeles County later this year, an Infotec spokesman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call Infotec at (714) 755-7776. 
</P>
</TEXT>
