<HEADLINE>
<P>
ETHNIC CONCERTS WILL BE HARD TO FIND AT CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK VANDERKNYFF, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ethnic music and dance will have a lower profile at the Orange County 
Performing Arts Center in the coming season. But the executive director of the 
Orange County Philharmonic Society, which books the hall, says it's more a 
result of scheduling conflicts than a replay of last season's philosophical 
conflicts with now-departed center management. 
</P>
<P>
 Of OCPS programs announced Wednesday for the center, only a performance Oct. 6 
by Teatro de Danza Espanola can be said to fall outside the standard classical 
repertory. OCPS will be presenting ethnic programs at other venues. 
</P>
<P>
 But executive director Dean Corey said the ethnic programs were "not opposed 
by the center" this time. Rather, Corey said that because he took over his job 
in August, he got a late start on programming and found that performers and/or 
the center already were booked.  
</P>
<P>
 The upcoming season includes three ethnic concerts, one fewer than in OCPS' 
current season. This year's programs -- the Chieftains, Mariachi los Camperos 
de Nati Cano, Les Ballets Africains from the Republic of Guinea and the 
Hungarian State Folk Ensemble -- had been opposed as "non-classical" by 
now-departed center president Thomas R. Kendrick. 
</P>
<P>
 Kendrick ultimately was overruled by the center board, but the issue was left 
unresolved for future seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 Corey said Wednesday that some aspects of the ethnic programming matter still 
have to be discussed by OCPS and center officials but that they do not involve 
programming philosophy so much as "defining a line of demarcation" between what 
the two organizations offer, basically the question of who presents what. 
</P>
<P>
 Corey added that his relationship with the new center management has gone 
smoothly.  
</P>
<P>
 Of the groups performing this year, only Mariachi los Camperos de Nati Cano 
will return to Orange County under OCPS' sponsorship next year -- to perform at 
UC Irvine. OCPS will present Le Ballet National du Senegal, a West African 
troupe, at the Irvine Barclay Theatre, and Teatro de Danza Espanola at the 
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
